    "reasoning": "First, consider the linear monic polynomial $ f(x) = x + c $ with integer coefficients. The condition requires $ p \\mid 2(f(p)!) + 1 $ for all sufficiently large primes $ p $. For $ f(p) = p + c $, if $ c \\geq 0 $, $ (p + c)! \\equiv 0 \\mod p $, leading to $ 2(f(p)!) + 1 \\equiv 1 \\mod p \\neq 0 $. For $ c < 0 $, let $ c = -m $ ($ m > 0 $), so $ f(p) = p - m $. Using Wilson's theorem, $ (p - 1)! \\equiv -1 \\mod p $. Expanding $ (p - 1)! = (p - 1)(p - 2)\\cdots(p - m + 1)(p - m)! $, we get $ (-1)^{m-1}(m-1)!(p - m)! \\equiv -1 \\mod p $. Solving $ 2(p - m)! \\equiv -1 \\mod p $ leads to $ (m - 1)! = 2 $, which holds for $ m = 3 $. Thus, $ f(x) = x - 3 $, constant term $ -3 $, so $ k = | -3 | = 3 $, and $ d = k - 2 = 1 $.\n\nNext, check if a function $ f: \\mathbb{R} \\to \\mathbb{R} $ exists satisfying (i) surjectivity and (ii) $ f(f(x)) = (x - 1)f(x) + 2 $. Known values: $ f(0) = 2 $, $ f(1) = 0 $, $ f(2) = 0 $, $ f(-1) = 1 $. The functional equation holds for these values. Using the axiom of choice, partition $ \\mathbb{R} $ into chains/cycles (e.g., $ -1 \\to 1 \\to 0 \\leftrightarrow 2 $) and define $ f $ recursively to satisfy the equation while ensuring surjectivity. No contradictions arise, so such a function exists.",
    "answer": "yes"
}
